[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Such examples may arouse suspicions of being generated by a different mechanism, or appear inconsistent with the remainder of that set of data.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection finds application in many domains including cybersecurity, medicine, machine vision, statistics, neuroscience, law enforcement and financial fraud to name only a few.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Anomalies were initially searched for clear rejection or omission from the data to aid statistical analysis, for example to compute the mean or standard deviation.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] They were also removed to better predictions from models such as linear regression, and more recently their removal aids the performance of machine learning algorithms.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] However, in many applications anomalies themselves are of interest and are the observations most desirous in the entire data set, which need to be identified and separated from noise or irrelevant outliers.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Many attempts have been made in the statistical and computer science communities to define an anomaly.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] The concept of intrusion detection, a critical component of anomaly detection, has evolved significantly over time.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Initially, it was a manual process where system administrators would monitor for unusual activities, such as a vacationing user's account being accessed or unexpected printer activity.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] This approach was not scalable and was soon superseded by the analysis of audit logs and system logs for signs of malicious behavior.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] By the late 1970s and early 1980s, the analysis of these logs was primarily used retrospectively to investigate incidents, as the volume of data made it impractical for real-time monitoring.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] The affordability of digital storage eventually led to audit logs being analyzed online, with specialized programs being developed to sift through the data.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] These programs, however, were typically run during off-peak hours due to their computational intensity.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] The 1990s brought the advent of real-time intrusion detection systems capable of analyzing audit data as it was generated, allowing for immediate detection of and response to attacks.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] This marked a significant shift towards proactive intrusion detection.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] As the field has continued to develop, the focus has shifted to creating solutions that can be efficiently implemented across large and complex network environments, adapting to the ever-growing variety of security threats and the dynamic nature of modern computing infrastructures.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is applicable in a very large number and variety of domains, and is an important subarea of unsupervised machine learning.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] As such it has applications in cyber-security, intrusion detection, fraud detection, fault detection, system health monitoring, event detection in sensor networks, detecting ecosystem disturbances, defect detection in images using machine vision, medical diagnosis and law enforcement.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection was proposed for intrusion detection systems (IDS) by Dorothy Denning in 1986.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection for IDS is normally accomplished with thresholds and statistics, but can also be done with soft computing, and inductive learning.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Types of features proposed by 1999 included profiles of users, workstations, networks, remote hosts, groups of users, and programs based on frequencies, means, variances, covariances, and standard deviations.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] The counterpart of anomaly detection in intrusion detection is misuse detection.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is vital in fintech for fraud prevention.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Preprocessing data to remove anomalies can be an important step in data analysis, and is done for a number of reasons.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Statistics such as the mean and standard deviation are more accurate after the removal of anomalies, and the visualisation of data can also be improved.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] In supervised learning, removing the anomalous data from the dataset often results in a statistically significant increase in accuracy.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection has become increasingly vital in video surveillance to enhance security and safety.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] With the advent of deep learning technologies, methods using Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and Simple Recurrent Units (SRUs) have shown significant promise in identifying unusual activities or behaviors in video data.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] These models can process and analyze extensive video feeds in real-time, recognizing patterns that deviate from the norm, which may indicate potential security threats or safety violations.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] An important aspect for video surveillance is the development of scalable real-time frameworks.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Such pipelines are required for processing multiple video streams with low computational resources.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] In IT infrastructure management, anomaly detection is crucial for ensuring the smooth operation and reliability of services.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] These are complex systems, composed of many interactive elements and large data quantities, requiring methods to process and reduce this data into a human and machine interpretable format.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Techniques like the IT Infrastructure Library (ITIL) and monitoring frameworks are employed to track and manage system performance and user experience.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Detected anomalies can help identify and pre-empt potential performance degradations or system failures, thus maintaining productivity and business process effectiveness.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is critical for the security and efficiency of Internet of Things (IoT) systems.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] It helps in identifying system failures and security breaches in complex networks of IoT devices.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] The methods must manage real-time data, diverse device types, and scale effectively.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Garg et al. have introduced a multi-stage anomaly detection framework that improves upon traditional methods by incorporating spatial clustering, density-based clustering, and locality-sensitive hashing.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] This tailored approach is designed to better handle the vast and varied nature of IoT data, thereby enhancing security and operational reliability in smart infrastructure and industrial IoT systems.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is crucial in the petroleum industry for monitoring critical machinery.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] A 2015 paper proposed a novel segmentation algorithm using support vector machines to analyze sensor data for real-time anomaly detection.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] In the oil and gas sector, anomaly detection is not just crucial for maintenance and safety, but also for environmental protection.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Aljameel et al. propose an advanced machine learning-based model for detecting minor leaks in oil and gas pipelines, a task traditional methods may miss.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Many anomaly detection techniques have been proposed in literature.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] The performance of methods usually depend on the data sets.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] For example, some may be suited to detecting local outliers, while others global, and methods have little systematic advantages over another when compared across many data sets.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Almost all algorithms also require the setting of non-intuitive parameters critical for performance, and usually unknown before application.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] The size of bins are key to the effectiveness of this technique but must be determined by the implementer.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] A more sophisticated technique uses kernel functions to approximate the distribution of the normal data.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Instances in low probability areas of the distribution are then considered anomalies.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Quantum machine learning approaches have been investigated for anomaly detection on near-term quantum hardware.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Quantum support vector machines (QSVMs) using quantum kernel methods, such as the ZZFeatureMap, have been applied to classification of normal versus anomalous instances by leveraging high-dimensional quantum feature spaces.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Histogram-based Outlier Score (HBOS) uses value histograms and assumes feature independence for fast predictions.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Dynamic networks, such as those representing financial systems, social media interactions, and transportation infrastructure, are subject to constant change, making anomaly detection within them a complex task.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Unlike static graphs, dynamic networks reflect evolving relationships and states, requiring adaptive techniques for anomaly detection.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] Many of the methods discussed above only yield an anomaly score prediction, which often can be explained to users as the point being in a region of low data density (or relatively low density compared to the neighbor's densities).
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/anomaly-detection] In explainable artificial intelligence, the users demand methods with higher explainability.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] Behavioral analytics can be useful as authentication as for security purposes.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] It uses non-identifiable but individually unique factors to confirm the identity of the user.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] The identity of the user is authenticated in the background using factors such as mouse movement, typing speed and habits, login history network detail like IP address, browser used, etc.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] Behavioral analytics utilizes the massive volumes of raw user event data captured during sessions in which consumers use applications, games, or websites, including traffic data like navigation paths, clicks, social media interactions, purchasing decisions and marketing responsiveness.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] Event-data can include advertising metrics like click-to-conversion time, as well as comparisons between other metrics like the monetary value of an order and the amount of time spent on the site.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] These data points are then compiled and analyzed, whether by looking at session progression from when a user first entered the platform until a sale was made, or what other products a user bought or looked at before this purchase.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] Behavioral analysis allows future actions and trends to be predicted based on the collection of such data.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] While business analytics has a more broad focus on the who, what, where and when of business intelligence, behavioral analytics narrows that scope, allowing one to take seemingly unrelated data points in order to extrapolate, predict and determine errors and future trends.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] It takes a more holistic and human view of data, connecting individual data points to tell us not only what is happening, but also how and why it is happening.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] Data shows that a large percentage of users using a certain eCommerce platform found it by searching for “Thai food” on Google.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] After landing on the homepage, most people spent some time on the “Asian Food” page and then logged off without placing an order.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] Looking at each of these events as separate data points does not represent what is really going on and why people did not make a purchase.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] However, viewing these data points as a representation of overall user behavior enables one to interpolate how and why users acted in this particular case.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] Behavioral analytics looks at all site traffic and page views as a timeline of connected events that did not lead to orders.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] Since most users left after viewing the “Asian Food” page, there could be a disconnect between what they are searching for on Google and what the “Asian Food” page displays.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] Knowing this, a quick look at the “Asian Food” page reveals that it does not display Thai food prominently and thus people do not think it is actually offered, even though it is.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] Behavioral analytics is common practice in commercial environments.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] Amazon.com is a leader in using behavioral analytics to recommend additional products that customers are likely to buy based on their previous purchasing patterns on the site.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] Behavioral analytics is also used by Target to suggest products to customers in their retail stores, while political campaigns use it to determine how potential voters should be approached.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] In addition to retail and political applications, behavioral analytics is also used by banks and manufacturing firms to prioritize leads generated by their websites.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] Behavioral analytics also allow developers to manage users in online-gaming and web applications.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] Amongst others, IBM and Intel are creating advanced analytics solutions.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/behavioral-analytics] In retail, this is IoT for tracking shopping behaviors (in-store tracking).
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] In statistics, **correlation** is a type of statistical relationship between two random variables or bivariate data.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] It usually refers to the extent to which a pair of quantities are linearly related.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] More generally, an arbitrary relationship between variables is called an **association**, meaning the degree to which the variability in one can be accounted for by the other.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The presence of a correlation is not sufficient to infer the presence of a causal relationship, and this is often stated as "correlation does not imply causation".
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Furthermore, the concept of correlation is not the same as dependence: if two variables are independent, then they are uncorrelated, but the opposite is not necessarily true – even if two variables are uncorrelated, they might be dependent on each other.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Correlations are useful because they can indicate a predictive relationship that can be exploited in practice.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] For example, an electrical utility may produce less power on a mild day based on the correlation between electricity demand and weather.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] In this example, there is a causal relationship, because extreme weather causes people to use more electricity for heating or cooling.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] There are several correlation coefficients that may be used to measure correlation, often denoted $\rho$ or r .
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The most common of these is the **Pearson correlation coefficient**, which is sensitive only to a linear relationship between two variables (which in turn may be present even when one variable is a nonlinear function of the other).
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Other correlation coefficients, such as **Spearman's rank correlation coefficient**, have been developed to be more robust than Pearson's and to detect less structured relationships between variables.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The concept has been generalized to other forms of association between two variables, such as mutual information and distance covariance.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The most familiar measure of dependence between two quantities is the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient, most commonly called 'Pearson's correlation coefficient' or simply 'the correlation coefficient' (as it is the most common variant).
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] It is obtained by taking the ratio of the covariance between two variables of a numerical dataset normalized to the square root of their variances.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Equivalently, Pearson's correlation coefficient can be calculated by dividing the covariance of the two variables by the product of their standard deviations.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Karl Pearson developed the coefficient from a similar idea by Francis Galton.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] A Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient attempts to establish a line of best fit through a dataset of two variables by essentially laying out the expected values and the resulting Pearson's correlation coefficient indicates how far away the actual dataset is from the expected values.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Depending on the sign of the Pearson's correlation coefficient, the result can be either a negative or positive correlation if there is any sort of relationship between the variables in the data set.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] where $\operatorname {E}$ is the expected value operator, $\operatorname {cov}$ means covariance, and $\operatorname {corr}$ is a widely used alternative notation for the correlation coefficient.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The Pearson correlation is defined only if both standard deviations are finite and positive.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] It is a corollary of the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality that the absolute value of the Pearson correlation coefficient is not bigger than 1.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Therefore, the value of a correlation coefficient ranges between −1 and +1.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] As it approaches zero there is less of a relationship (closer to uncorrelated).
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The closer the coefficient is to either −1 or 1, the stronger the correlation between the variables.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] If the variables are independent, Pearson's correlation coefficient is 0.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] However, because the correlation coefficient detects only linear dependencies between two variables, the converse is not necessarily true.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] A correlation coefficient of 0 does not imply that the variables are independent.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] For example, suppose the random variable X is symmetrically distributed about zero, and $Y=X^{2}$ .
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Then Y is completely determined by X , so that X and Y are perfectly dependent, but their correlation is zero; they are uncorrelated.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] However, in the special case when X and Y are jointly normal, uncorrelatedness is equivalent to independence.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Even though uncorrelated data does not necessarily imply independence, one can check if random variables are independent if their mutual information is 0.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Given a series of n measurements of the pair $(X_{i},Y_{i})$ indexed by $i=1,\ldots ,n$ , the *sample correlation coefficient* can be used to estimate the population Pearson correlation $\rho _{X,Y}$ between X and Y .
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] where ${\overline {x}}$ and ${\overline {y}}$ are the sample means of X and Y , and $s_{x}$ and $s_{y}$ are the corrected sample standard deviations of X and Y .
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] where $s'_{x}$ and $s'_{y}$ are the *uncorrected* sample standard deviations of X and Y .
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] If x and y are results of measurements that contain measurement error, the realistic limits on the correlation coefficient are not −1 to +1 but a smaller range.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] For the case of a linear model with a single independent variable, the coefficient of determination (R squared) is the square of $r_{xy}$ , Pearson's product-moment coefficient.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Consider the joint probability distribution of X and Y given in the table below.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Rank correlation coefficients, such as Spearman's rank correlation coefficient and Kendall's rank correlation coefficient (τ) measure the extent to which, as one variable increases, the other variable tends to increase, without requiring that increase to be represented by a linear relationship.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] If, as the one variable increases, the other *decreases*, the rank correlation coefficients will be negative.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] It is common to regard these rank correlation coefficients as alternatives to Pearson's coefficient, used either to reduce the amount of calculation or to make the coefficient less sensitive to non-normality in distributions.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] As we go from each pair to the next pair, x increases, and so does y .
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] This relationship is perfect, in the sense that an increase in x is *always* accompanied by an increase in y .
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] This means that we have a perfect rank correlation, and both Spearman's and Kendall's correlation coefficients are 1, whereas in this example Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient is 0.7544, indicating that the points are far from lying on a straight line.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] In the same way if y always *decreases* when x *increases*, the rank correlation coefficients will be −1, while the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient may or may not be close to −1, depending on how close the points are to a straight line.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Although in the extreme cases of perfect rank correlation the two coefficients are both equal (being both +1 or both −1), this is not generally the case, and so values of the two coefficients cannot meaningfully be compared.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] For example, for the three pairs (1, 1) (2, 3) (3, 2) Spearman's coefficient is 1/2, while Kendall's coefficient is 1/3.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The conventional dictum that "correlation does not imply causation" means that correlation cannot be used by itself to infer a causal relationship between the variables.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] This dictum should not be taken to mean that correlations cannot indicate the potential existence of causal relations.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] However, the causes underlying the correlation, if any, may be indirect and unknown, and high correlations also overlap with identity relations (tautologies), where no causal process exists (e.g., between two variables measuring the same construct).
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Consequently, a correlation between two variables is not a sufficient condition to establish a causal relationship (in either direction).
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] A correlation between age and height in children is fairly causally transparent, but a correlation between mood and health in people is less so.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Does improved mood lead to improved health, or does good health lead to good mood, or both?
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Or does some other factor underlie both?
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] In other words, a correlation can be taken as evidence for a possible causal relationship, but cannot indicate what the causal relationship, if any, might be.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The Pearson correlation coefficient indicates the strength of a *linear* relationship between two variables, but its value generally does not completely characterize their relationship.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] In particular, if the conditional mean of Y given X , denoted $\operatorname {E} (Y\mid X)$ , is not linear in X , the correlation coefficient will not fully determine the form of $\operatorname {E} (Y\mid X)$ .
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The adjacent image shows scatter plots of Anscombe's quartet, a set of four different pairs of variables created by Francis Anscombe.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The four y variables have the same mean (7.5), variance (4.12), correlation (0.816) and regression line ( ${\textstyle y=3+0.5x}$ ).
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] However, as can be seen on the plots, the distribution of the variables is very different.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The first one (top left) seems to be distributed normally, and corresponds to what one would expect when considering two variables correlated and following the assumption of normality.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The second one (top right) is not distributed normally; while an obvious relationship between the two variables can be observed, it is not linear.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] In this case the Pearson correlation coefficient does not indicate that there is an exact functional relationship: only the extent to which that relationship can be approximated by a linear relationship.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] In the third case (bottom left), the linear relationship is perfect, except for one outlier which exerts enough influence to lower the correlation coefficient from 1 to 0.816.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Finally, the fourth example (bottom right) shows another example when one outlier is enough to produce a high correlation coefficient, even though the relationship between the two variables is not linear.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] These examples indicate that the correlation coefficient, as a summary statistic, cannot replace visual examination of the data.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The examples are sometimes said to demonstrate that the Pearson correlation assumes that the data follow a normal distribution, but this is only partially correct.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The Pearson correlation can be accurately calculated for any distribution that has a finite covariance matrix, which includes most distributions encountered in practice.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] However, the Pearson correlation coefficient (taken together with the sample mean and variance) is only a sufficient statistic if the data is drawn from a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] As a result, the Pearson correlation coefficient fully characterizes the relationship between variables if and only if the data are drawn from a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Similarly for two stochastic processes $\left\{X_{t}\right\}_{t\in {\mathcal {T}}}$ and $\left\{Y_{t}\right\}_{t\in {\mathcal {T}}}$ : If they are independent, then they are uncorrelated.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The opposite of this statement might not be true.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Even if two variables are uncorrelated, they might not be independent of each other.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The degree of dependence between variables X and Y does not depend on the scale on which the variables are expressed.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] That is, if we are analyzing the relationship between X and Y, most correlation measures are unaffected by transforming X to *a* + *bX* and Y to *c* + *dY*, where *a*, *b*, *c*, and *d* are constants (*b* and *d* being positive).
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] This is true of some correlation statistics as well as their population analogues.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Some correlation statistics, such as the rank correlation coefficient, are also invariant to monotone transformations of the marginal distributions of X and/or Y.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Most correlation measures are sensitive to the manner in which X and Y are sampled.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Dependencies tend to be stronger if viewed over a wider range of values.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Several techniques have been developed that attempt to correct for range restriction in one or both variables, and are commonly used in meta-analysis; the most common are Thorndike's case II and case III equations.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Various correlation measures in use may be undefined for certain joint distributions of X and Y.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] For example, the Pearson correlation coefficient is defined in terms of moments, and hence will be undefined if the moments are undefined.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Measures of dependence based on quantiles are always defined.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Sample-based statistics intended to estimate population measures of dependence may or may not have desirable statistical properties such as being unbiased, or asymptotically consistent, based on the spatial structure of the population from which the data were sampled.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Sensitivity to the data distribution can be used to an advantage.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] For example, scaled correlation is designed to use the sensitivity to the range in order to pick out correlations between fast components of time series.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] By reducing the range of values in a controlled manner, the correlations on long time scale are filtered out and only the correlations on short time scales are revealed.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Thus the diagonal entries are all identically one.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] If the measures of correlation used are product-moment coefficients, the correlation matrix is the same as the covariance matrix of the standardized random variables $X_{i}/\sigma (X_{i})$ for $i=1,\dots ,n$ .
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] This applies both to the matrix of population correlations (in which case $\sigma$ is the population standard deviation), and to the matrix of sample correlations (in which case $\sigma$ denotes the sample standard deviation).
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Consequently, each is necessarily a positive-semidefinite matrix.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Moreover, the correlation matrix is strictly positive definite if no variable can have all its values exactly generated as a linear function of the values of the others.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The correlation matrix is symmetric because the correlation between $X_{i}$ and $X_{j}$ is the same as the correlation between $X_{j}$ and $X_{i}$ .
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] A correlation matrix appears, for example, in one formula for the coefficient of multiple determination, a measure of goodness of fit in multiple regression.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] In statistical modelling, correlation matrices representing the relationships between variables are categorized into different correlation structures, which are distinguished by factors such as the number of parameters required to estimate them.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] For example, in an exchangeable correlation matrix, all pairs of variables are modeled as having the same correlation, so all non-diagonal elements of the matrix are equal to each other.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] On the other hand, an autoregressive matrix is often used when variables represent a time series, since correlations are likely to be greater when measurements are closer in time.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Other examples include independent, unstructured, M-dependent, and Toeplitz.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] In exploratory data analysis, the iconography of correlations consists in replacing a correlation matrix by a diagram where the "remarkable" correlations are represented by a solid line (positive correlation), or a dotted line (negative correlation).
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] In some applications (e.g., building data models from only partially observed data) one wants to find the "nearest" correlation matrix to an "approximate" correlation matrix (e.g., a matrix which typically lacks positive semi-definiteness due to the way it has been computed).
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] In 2002, Higham formalized the notion of nearness using the Frobenius norm and provided a method for computing the nearest correlation matrix using the Dykstra's projection algorithm.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] This sparked interest in the subject, with new theoretical (e.g., computing the nearest correlation matrix with factor structure) and numerical (e.g. usage of Newton's method for computing the nearest correlation matrix) results obtained in the subsequent years.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] where $\operatorname {\boldsymbol {\mathcal {E}}} (X)$ and $\operatorname {\boldsymbol {\mathcal {E}}} (Y)$ are the expected values of $\ X\$ and $\ Y\ ,$ respectively, and $\ \sigma _{X}\$ and $\ \sigma _{Y}\$ are the standard deviations of $\ X\$ and $\ Y\ ,$ respectively.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] where $\ F_{Hyp}\$ is the Gaussian hypergeometric function.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] This density is both a Bayesian posterior density and an exact optimal confidence distribution density.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The information given by a correlation coefficient is not enough to define the dependence structure between random variables.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The correlation coefficient completely defines the dependence structure only in very particular cases, for example when the distribution is a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] (See diagram above.) In the case of elliptical distributions it characterizes the (hyper-)ellipses of equal density; however, it does not completely characterize the dependence structure (for example, a multivariate t-distribution's degrees of freedom determine the level of tail dependence).
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] For continuous variables, multiple alternative measures of dependence were introduced to address the deficiency of Pearson's correlation that it can be zero for dependent random variables (see and references therein for an overview).
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] They all share the important property that a value of zero implies independence.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] This led some authors to recommend their routine usage, particularly of distance correlation.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Another alternative measure is the Randomized Dependence Coefficient.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The RDC is a computationally efficient, copula-based measure of dependence between multivariate random variables and is invariant with respect to non-linear scalings of random variables.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] One important disadvantage of the alternative, more general measures is that, when used to test whether two variables are associated, they tend to have lower power compared to Pearson's correlation when the data follow a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] This is an implication of the No free lunch theorem.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] To detect all kinds of relationships, these measures have to sacrifice power on other relationships, particularly for the important special case of a linear relationship with Gaussian marginals, for which Pearson's correlation is optimal.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Another problem concerns interpretation.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] While Pearson's correlation can be interpreted for all values, the alternative measures can generally only be interpreted meaningfully at the extremes.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] For two binary variables, the odds ratio measures their dependence, and takes a range of non-negative numbers, possibly infinity: ⁠ $[0,+\infty ]$ ⁠.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] Related statistics such as Yule's *Y* and Yule's *Q* normalize this to the correlation-like range ⁠ $[-1,1]$ ⁠.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/correlation] The odds ratio is generalized by the logistic model to model cases where the dependent variables are discrete and there may be one or more independent variables.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/insider-threat] An **insider threat** is a perceived threat to an organization that comes from people within the organization, such as employees, former employees, contractors or business associates, who have inside information concerning the organization's security practices, data and computer systems.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/insider-threat] The threat may involve fraud, the theft of confidential or commercially valuable information, the theft of intellectual property, or the sabotage of computer systems.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/insider-threat] Insiders have legitimate access to computer systems and are often familiar with the organization's data and intellectual property.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/insider-threat] Thus Insider threats are harder to defend against than attacks from outsiders.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/insider-threat] The CERT Coordination Center at Carnegie-Mellon University maintains the CERT Insider Threat Center, which includes a database of more than 850 cases of insider threats, including instances of fraud, theft and sabotage; the database is used for research and analysis.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/insider-threat] In the 2022 Data Breach Investigations Report (DBIR), Verizon found that 82% of breaches involved the human element, noting that employees continue to play a leading role in cybersecurity incidents and breaches.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/insider-threat] According to the UK Information Commissioners Office, 90% of all breaches reported to them in 2019 were the result of mistakes made by end users.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/insider-threat] This was up from 61% and 87% over the previous two years.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/insider-threat] A 2018 whitepaper reported that 53% of companies surveyed had confirmed insider attacks against their organization in the previous 12 months, with 27% saying insider attacks have become more frequent.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/insider-threat] The insider was identified in 74% of cases.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/insider-threat] Financial gain was a motive in 81% of cases, revenge in 23% of cases, and 27% of the people carrying out malicious acts were in financial difficulties at the time.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/insider-threat] The US Department of Defense Personnel Security Research Center published a report that describes approaches for detecting insider threats.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/insider-threat] Earlier it published ten case studies of insider attacks by information technology professionals.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/insider-threat] Multiple classification systems and ontologies have been proposed to classify insider threats.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/insider-threat] Insider threat research has been criticized.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/insider-threat] Adopting sociotechnical approaches, researchers have also argued for the need to consider insider threat from the perspective of social systems.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM tools can be implemented as software, hardware, or managed services.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems log security events and generate reports to meet regulatory frameworks such as the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) and the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS).
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] The integration of SIM and SEM within SIEM provides organizations with a centralized approach for monitoring security events and responding to threats in real-time.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] In recent years, SIEM has become increasingly incorporated into national cybersecurity initiatives.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] For instance, Executive Order 14028 signed in 2021 by U.S.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] President Joseph Biden mandates the use of SIEM technologies to improve incident detection and reporting in federal systems.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Compliance with these mandates is further reinforced by frameworks such as NIST SP 800-92, which outlines best practices for managing computer security logs.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Modern SIEM platforms are aggregating and normalizing data not only from various Information Technology (IT) sources, but from production and manufacturing Operational Technology (OT) environments as well.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Initially, system logging was primarily used for troubleshooting and debugging.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] However, as operating systems and networks have grown more complex, so has the generation of system logs.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] The monitoring of system logs has also become increasingly common due to the rise of sophisticated cyberattacks and the need for compliance with regulatory frameworks, which mandate logging security controls within risk management frameworks (RMF).
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Starting in the late 1970s, working groups began establishing criteria for managing auditing and monitoring programs, laying the groundwork for modern cybersecurity practices, such as insider threat detection and incident response.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] A key publication during this period was NIST’s Special Publication 500-19.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] In 2005, the term "SIEM" (Security Information and Event Management) was introduced by Gartner analysts Mark Nicolett and Amrit Williams.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems provide a single interface for gathering security data from information systems and presenting it as actionable intelligence.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] With the implementation of RMFs globally, auditing and monitoring have become central to information assurance and security.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Cybersecurity professionals now rely on logging data to perform real-time security functions, driven by governance models that incorporate these processes into analytical tasks.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] As information assurance matured in the late 1990s and into the 2000s, the need to centralize system logs became apparent.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Centralized log management allows for easier oversight and coordination across networked systems.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] President Joseph Biden signed Executive Order 14028, "Improving the Nation's Cybersecurity," which established further logging requirements, including audit logging and endpoint protection, to enhance incident response capabilities.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] This order was a response to an increase in ransomware attacks targeting critical infrastructure.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] By reinforcing information assurance controls within RMFs, the order aimed to drive compliance and secure funding for cybersecurity initiatives.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Published in September 2006, the NIST SP 800-92 Guide to Computer Security Log Management serves as a key document within the NIST Risk Management Framework to guide what should be auditable.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] As indicated by the absence of the term "SIEM", the document was released before the widespread adoption of SIEM technologies.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Although the guide is not exhaustive due to rapid changes in technology since its publication, it remains relevant by anticipating industry growth.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] NIST is not the only source of guidance on regulatory mechanisms for auditing and monitoring, and many organizations are encouraged to adopt SIEM solutions rather than relying solely on host-based checks.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Public and private organizations frequently reference NIST documents in their security policies.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] NIST SP 800-53 AU-2 Event Monitoring is a key security control that supports system auditing and ensures continuous monitoring for information assurance and cybersecurity operations.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM solutions are typically employed as central tools for these efforts.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Federal systems categorized based on their impact on confidentiality, integrity, and availability (CIA) have five specific logging requirements (AU-2 a-e) that must be met.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] While logging every action is possible, it is generally not recommended due to the volume of logs and the need for actionable security data.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] AU-2 provides a foundation for organizations to build a logging strategy that aligns with other controls.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] NIST SP 800-53 SI-4 System Monitoring outlines the requirements for monitoring systems, including detecting unauthorized access and tracking anomalies, malware, and potential attacks.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] This security control specifies both the hardware and software requirements for detecting suspicious activities.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Similarly, NIST SP 800-53 RA-10 Threat Hunting, added in Revision 5, emphasizes proactive network defense by identifying threats that evade traditional controls.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM solutions play a critical role in aggregating security information for threat hunting teams.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Together, AU-2, SI-4, and RA-10 demonstrate how NIST controls integrate into a comprehensive security strategy.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] These controls, supported by SIEM solutions, help ensure continuous monitoring, risk assessments, and in-depth defense mechanisms across federal and private networks.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] In practice many products in this area will have a mix of these functions, so there will often be some overlap – and many commercial vendors also promote their own terminology.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Oftentimes commercial vendors provide different combinations of these functionalities which tend to improve SIEM overall.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Log management alone doesn't provide real-time insights on network security, SEM on its own won't provide complete data for deep threat analysis.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] When SEM and log management are combined, more information is available for SIEM to monitor.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] A key focus is to monitor and help manage user and service privileges, directory services and other system-configuration changes; as well as providing log auditing and review and incident response.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM architectures may vary by vendor; however, generally, essential components comprise the SIEM engine.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] A basic SIEM infrastructure is depicted in the image to the right.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Computer security researcher Chris Kubecka identified the following SIEM use cases, presented at the hacking conference 28C3 (Chaos Communication Congress).
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Modern SIEM platforms support not only detection, but response too.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] The response can be manual or automated including AI based response.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems play a significant role in helping organizations meet regulatory compliance requirements by centralizing log collection, enabling real-time monitoring, and generating audit-ready reports.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Under the HIPAA Security Rule, covered entities must implement audit controls that record and examine activity in information systems containing electronic protected health information (ePHI).
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] A proposed update to the HIPAA Security Rule (NPRM, December 2024) would require covered entities to deploy technology capable of detecting and responding to security incidents within 24 hours, a capability commonly provided by SIEM platforms.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 10 mandates that organizations track and monitor all access to network resources and cardholder data, with SIEM systems commonly used to aggregate and analyze the required log data across distributed environments.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Similarly, the Sarbanes-Oxley Act (SOX) requires organizations to maintain audit trails for financial system access, and SIEM platforms provide the centralized logging and retention capabilities necessary to demonstrate compliance during audits.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems can have hundreds and thousands of correlation rules.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Some of these are simple, and some are more complex.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Once a correlation rule is triggered the system can take appropriate steps to mitigate a cyber attack.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Usually, this includes sending a notification to a user and then possibly limiting or even shutting down the system.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Brute force detection is relatively straightforward.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Brute forcing relates to continually trying to guess a variable.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] It most commonly refers to someone trying to constantly guess your password - either manually or with a tool.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] However, it can refer to trying to guess URLs or important file locations on your system.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] An automated brute force is easy to detect as someone trying to enter their password 60 times in a minute is impossible.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] When a user logs in to a system, generally speaking, it creates a timestamp of the event.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Alongside the time, the system may often record other useful information such as the device used, physical location, IP address, incorrect login attempts, etc.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] The more data is collected the more use can be gathered from it.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] For impossible travel, the system looks at the current and last login date/time and the difference between the recorded distances.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] If it deems it's not possible for this to happen, for example traveling hundreds of miles within a minute, then it will set off a warning.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Many employees and users are now using VPN services which may obscure physical location.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] This should be taken into consideration when setting up such a rule.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] The average user does not typically copy or move files on the system repeatedly.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Thus, any excessive file copying on a system could be attributed to an attacker wanting to cause harm to an organization.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Unfortunately, it's not as simple as stating someone has gained access to your network illegally and wants to steal confidential information.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] It could also be an employee looking to sell company information, or they could just want to take home some files for the weekend.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Monitoring network traffic against unusual patterns that includes any threats or attacks ranging from DDOS to network scans.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Note SIEM can monitor data flow in the network and to detect and prevent potential data exfiltration efforts.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] In general dedicated Data loss prevention (DLP) take care about data loss prevention.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] A DDoS (distributed denial of service) attack could cause significant damage to a company or organization.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] A DDoS attack can not only take a website offline, it can also make a system weaker.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] With suitable correlation rules in place, a SIEM should trigger an alert at the start of the attack so that the company can take the necessary precautionary measures to protect vital systems.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] File integrity and change monitoring (FIM) is the process of monitoring the files on your system.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Unexpected changes in your system files will trigger an alert as it's a likely indication of a cyber attack.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/security-information-and-event-management] Some examples of customized rules to alert on event conditions involve user authentication rules, attacks detected and infections detected.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] The reason for using UBA, according to Johna Till Johnson from Nemertes Research, is that "security systems provide so much information that it is tough to uncover information that truly indicates a potential for a real attack.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] Analytics tools help make sense of the vast amount of data that SIEM, IDS/IPS, system logs, and other tools gather.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] UBA tools use a specialized type of security analytics that focuses on the behavior of systems and the people using them.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] UBA technology first evolved in the field of marketing, to help companies understand and predict consumer-buying patterns.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] The E in UEBA extends the analysis to include entity activities that take place but that are not necessarily directly linked or tied to a user's specific actions but that can still correlate to a vulnerability, reconnaissance, intrusion breach or exploit occurrence.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] The term "UEBA" was coined by Gartner in 2015.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] UEBA tracks the activity of devices, applications, servers and data.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] UEBA systems produce more data and provide more complex reporting options than UBA systems.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] UEBA tools differ from endpoint detection and response (EDR) capabilities in that UEBA is an analytic focus on the user behavior whereas EDR has an analytic focus on the endpoint.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] Cybersecurity solutions, like EDR and XDR, typically prioritize detection and response to external threats once an incident has occurred.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] EUBA and IRM solutions are looking for prevent potential risks internally by analyzing employee behavior.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] Continuous authentication has been proposed as a form of user behavior analytics in which a system verifies identity throughout an active session rather than only at login.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] By monitoring behavior during use, this approach reduces the risk of system abuse after initial access is granted.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] Research in this area has examined signals such as mouse movements, keystroke timing, network activity, and application usage patterns.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] These signals can form computer-usage profiles that remain consistent over long periods and differ across individuals, allowing machine-learning models to flag behavior that deviates from the user's typical patterns.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] Such systems may also use machine-learning models and anomaly detection to identify suspicious sessions based on deviations from ordinary interaction patterns.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] Machine-learning systems for continuous authentication typically rely on long-term data because everyday behavior drifts across hours, days, or weeks.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] Models must account for changes caused by fatigue, workload, or environmental context.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] This is why researchers distinguish offline evaluations, where models are tested on pre-collected datasets, from online evaluations, which observe behavior in real time and capture day-to-day variability.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] Continuous authentication is usually considered in environments where some degree of monitoring is already expected and where the expectation of privacy is lower, such as corporate settings.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] The same study also examined the temporal structure of computer-usage behavior.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] Using surrogate-data analysis, Giovanini et al. found strong 24-hour cycles in most users' activity patterns, indicating that daily routines shape usage profiles in a measurable way and that these profiles contain both time-dependent structure and random variation.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] This has led researchers to suggest that separating periodic patterns from background system processes may help improve model stability.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] Follow-up work in this space has noted that not all features used in continuous authentication necessarily reflect human behavior directly.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] In systems that collect data on running processes, contacted domains, keystroke timing, mouse movement, and web activity, many of the strongest predictive features come from network and application usage patterns rather than from human-generated motion.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] These characteristics often reflect device configuration or network environment and can sometimes cause models to distinguish devices rather than users.
[src:user-entity-behavior-analytics/user-behavior-analytics] This concern has been emphasized in recent studies on device bias, which show that authentication models may unintentionally learn hardware- or sensor-specific characteristics rather than behavioral traits.
